Why We're Here¶

Photo sharing and photo storage services like to have location data for each photo that is uploaded. With the location data, these services can build advanced features, such as automatic suggestion of relevant tags or automatic photo organization, which help provide a compelling user experience. Although a photo's location can often be obtained by looking at the photo's metadata, many photos uploaded to these services will not have location metadata available. This can happen when, for example, the camera capturing the picture does not have GPS or if a photo's metadata is scrubbed due to privacy concerns.

If no location metadata for an image is available, one way to infer the location is to detect and classify a discernable landmark in the image. Given the large number of landmarks across the world and the immense volume of images that are uploaded to photo sharing services, using human judgement to classify these landmarks would not be feasible.

In this notebook, you will take the first steps towards addressing this problem by building models to automatically predict the location of the image based on any landmarks depicted in the image. At the end of this project, your code will accept any user-supplied image as input and suggest the top k most relevant landmarks from 50 possible landmarks from across the world. The image below displays a potential sample output of your finished project.

Step 1: Create a CNN to Classify Landmarks (from Scratch)¶

In this step, you will create a CNN that classifies landmarks. You must create your CNN from scratch (so, you can't use transfer learning yet!), and you must attain a test accuracy of at least 20%.

Although 20% may seem low at first glance, it seems more reasonable after realizing how difficult of a problem this is. Many times, an image that is taken at a landmark captures a fairly mundane image of an animal or plant, like in the following picture.

Just by looking at that image alone, would you have been able to guess that it was taken at the Haleakalā National Park in Hawaii?

An accuracy of 20% is significantly better than random guessing, which would provide an accuracy of just 2%. In Step 2 of this notebook, you will have the opportunity to greatly improve accuracy by using transfer learning to create a CNN.

Remember that practice is far ahead of theory in deep learning. Experiment with many different architectures, and trust your intuition. And, of course, have fun!

### TODO: Write data loaders for training, validation, and test sets
## Specify appropriate transforms, and batch_sizes


batch_size = 32
valid_size = 0.25 # 20% of overall in 60/20/20 spliz

data_dir = 'landmark_images/'
train_data = data_dir + 'train/'



test_data = data_dir + 'test/'

train_transforms = transforms.Compose([transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
                                      transforms.RandomResizedCrop(224),
                                      transforms.RandomRotation(15),
                                      transforms.ColorJitter(brightness = 0.5),
                                      transforms.ToTensor(),
                                      transforms.Normalize((0.485, 0.456, 0.406), (0.229, 0.224, 0.225))])
basic_transforms = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize(256),
                                      transforms.CenterCrop(224),
                                      transforms.ToTensor(),
                                      transforms.Normalize((0.485, 0.456, 0.406), (0.229, 0.224, 0.225))])

train_set = datasets.ImageFolder(train_data, transform=train_transforms)
#valid_set = datasets.ImageFolder(valid_data, transform=basic_transforms)

test_set = datasets.ImageFolder(test_data, transform=basic_transforms)

# define dataloader parameters
# obtain training indices that will be used for validation

num_train = len(train_set)
indices = list(range(num_train))
np.random.shuffle(indices)
split = int(np.floor(valid_size * num_train))
train_idx, valid_idx = indices[split:], indices[:split]

# define samplers for obtaining training and validation batches
train_sampler = SubsetRandomSampler(train_idx)
valid_sampler = SubsetRandomSampler(valid_idx)

train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_set, batch_size=batch_size, sampler=train_sampler,
                                           num_workers=0)
valid_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_set,
                                           batch_size=batch_size,
                                           sampler=valid_sampler,
                                           num_workers=0)
test_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(test_set,
                                           batch_size=batch_size, 
                                           num_workers=0)







loaders_scratch = {'train': train_loader, 'valid': valid_loader, 'test': test_loader}
class_names = train_set.classes

def imshow(inp, title=None):
    

    inp = inp.numpy().transpose((1, 2, 0))
    mean = np.array([0.485, 0.456, 0.406])
    std = np.array([0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    inp = std * inp + mean
    inp = np.clip(inp, 0, 1)
    plt.imshow(inp)
    if title is not None:
        plt.title(title)

(IMPLEMENTATION) Model Architecture¶

Create a CNN to classify images of landmarks. Use the template in the code cell below.

In [7]:
# define the CNN architecture
class Net(nn.Module):
    ## TODO: choose an architecture, and complete the class
    def __init__(self):
        super(Net, self).__init__()
        
        ## Define layers of a CNN
        # (3x224x224)
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 6, 3, padding=1)
        #(6x112x112)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(6, 16, 3, padding=1)
        # (16x56x56)
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(16, 32, 3, padding=1)
        
        # pool
        self.pool = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)
        # (32x28x28 )
        # fully-connected layers
         
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(32*28*28, 1024)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(1024, 512)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(512, 50)
       

        # drop-out
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.2)
        
        
    
    def forward(self, x):
        ## Define forward behavior
        
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv1(x)))
        
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv2(x)))
        
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv3(x)))
        
        #flatten batch_size
        
        x = x.view(-1, 32*28*28)
        
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))
        
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = F.relu(self.fc2(x))
        
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.fc3(x)
        
        
        
        return x

#-#-# Do NOT modify the code below this line. #-#-#

# instantiate the CNN
model_scratch = Net()
print(model_scratch)
# move tensors to GPU if CUDA is available
if use_cuda:
    model_scratch.cuda()

Net(
  (conv1): Conv2d(3, 6, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1))
  (conv2): Conv2d(6, 16, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1))
  (conv3): Conv2d(16, 32, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1))
  (pool): MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2, padding=0, dilation=1, ceil_mode=False)
  (fc1): Linear(in_features=25088, out_features=1024, bias=True)
  (fc2): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=512, bias=True)
  (fc3): Linear(in_features=512, out_features=50, bias=True)
  (dropout): Dropout(p=0.2)
)

Question 2: Outline the steps you took to get to your final CNN architecture and your reasoning at each step.

Answer: The number of convolutional layers and number of nodes and layers in the fully connected layer section where adjusted to accomodate the data, and each parts setting to 3 layers was appropriate to, default Relu functions where used, as well as smaller kernel filters in the convolutional layers, which is more of a standard in newer modern architectures. To only deepen the tensors with the convolutional layers, the images where padded with 1 for the 3 kernel filter, so that only the maxpooling layer led to horizontal size reduction, and so that less information are lost between the layers. Dropout of 20% was set for a higher chance of training weights and biases of potentially less frequently used node connections in the network. The Adam optimizer was used and it was experimented with alpha and betas in several trials, whereas beta2 was set close to 1 for this computer vision problem.

Implement your training algorithm in the code cell below. Save the final model parameters at the filepath stored in the variable save_path.

def train(n_epochs, loaders, model, optimizer, criterion, use_cuda, save_path):
    """returns trained model"""
    # initialize tracker for minimum validation loss
    valid_loss_min = np.Inf
    
    for epoch in range(1, n_epochs+1):
        # initialize variables to monitor training and validation loss
        train_loss = 0.0
        valid_loss = 0.0
        
        
        ### TRAINING
        
        # set the module to training mode
        model.train()
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(train_loader):
            # move to GPU 
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()

            ## TODO: find the loss and update the model parameters accordingly
            ## record the average training loss, using something like
            ## train_loss = train_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data.item() - train_loss))
            
            # clearing gradients of variables
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            
            # forward pass
            output = model(data)
            
            # calculate loss
            loss = criterion(output, target)
            
            # backward pass
            loss.backward()
            
            # optimization step
            optimizer.step()
            
            # update training loss
            train_loss += loss.item()*data.size(0)

            
            

            
        ### VALIDATION
        
        # set the model to evaluation mode
        model.eval()
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(valid_loader):
            # move to GPU
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
            
            # forward pass for prediction
            output = model(data)
            
            # loss calculation
            loss = criterion(output, target)
            
            

            ## TODO: update average validation loss 
            valid_loss += loss.item()*data.size(0)

        
        # for displaying epochs, get average losses
        train_loss = train_loss/len(train_loader.sampler)
        valid_loss = valid_loss/len(valid_loader.sampler)
            
            

        # print training/validation statistics 
        print(f'Epoch: {epoch} \tTraining Loss: {train_loss:.6f} \tValidation Loss: {valid_loss:.6f}')

        ## TODO: if the validation loss has decreased, save the model at the filepath stored in save_path
        if valid_loss <= valid_loss_min:
            print(f'Validation loss decreased ({valid_loss_min:.6f} --> {valid_loss:.6f}).  Saving model ...')
            
            torch.save(model.state_dict(), save_path)
            valid_loss_min = valid_loss        

        
        
    return model

def custom_weight_init(m):
    ## TODO: implement a weight initialization strategy
    classname = m.__class__.__name__
    
    if classname.find('Linear') != -1:
        
        n = m.in_features
        y = (1.0/np.sqrt(n)) # general rule
        m.weight.data.normal_(0,y) # normal distribution centered around zero,
        m.bias.data.fill_(0)      # which is of advantage as numbers close to zero are
                                  # better for computation for nodes with more inputs
                

    
    

#-#-# Do NOT modify the code below this line. #-#-#
    
model_scratch.apply(custom_weight_init)

                      criterion_scratch, use_cuda, 'ignore.pt')

In [9]:
def test(loaders, model, criterion, use_cuda):

    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    # monitor test loss and accuracy
    test_loss = 0.
    correct = 0.
    total = 0.

    # set the module to evaluation mode
    model.eval()

    for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['test']):
        # move to GPU
        if use_cuda:
            data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
        # forward pass: compute predicted outputs by passing inputs to the model
        output = model(data)
        # calculate the loss
        loss = criterion(output, target)
        # update average test loss 
        test_loss = test_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data.item() - test_loss))
        # convert output probabilities to predicted class
        pred = output.data.max(1, keepdim=True)[1]
        # compare predictions to true label
        correct += np.sum(np.squeeze(pred.eq(target.data.view_as(pred))).cpu().numpy())
        total += data.size(0)
            
    print('Test Loss: {:.6f}\n'.format(test_loss))

    print('\nTest Accuracy: %2d%% (%2d/%2d)' % (
        100. * correct / total, correct, total))

Question 3: Outline the steps you took to get to your final CNN architecture and your reasoning at each step. Describe why you think the architecture is suitable for the current problem.

Answer: Since our dataset of images was very small, in computer scientific terms, it was omitted to train weights and biases of the pretrained model by completely freezing the network. Unfreezing some of those layers and performing "fine tuning" was only useful, when the dataset was 1. relatively large and trustworthy, 2. the type of data - in this case images - fundamentally different than those which the pretrained model is trained on. Since neither is the case here, to fully exploit prior work on standard image_data, all layers have been frozen, and resnet18 was chosen for its efficacy and historically high accuracy.

(IMPLEMENTATION) Train and Validate the Model¶

Train and validate your model in the code cell below. Save the final model parameters at filepath 'model_transfer.pt'.

def train(n_epochs, train_loader, valid_loader, model, optimizer, criterion, use_cuda, save_path):
    """returns trained model"""
    # initialize tracker for minimum validation loss
    valid_loss_min = np.Inf
    
    for epoch in range(1, n_epochs+1):
        # initialize variables to monitor training and validation loss
        train_loss = 0.0
        valid_loss = 0.0
        
        
        ### TRAINING

        # set the module to training mode
        model.train()
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(train_loader):
            # move to GPU 
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()

            ## TODO: find the loss and update the model parameters accordingly
            ## record the average training loss, using something like
            ## train_loss = train_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data.item() - train_loss))
            
            # clearing gradients of variables
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            
            # forward pass
            output = model(data)
            
            # calculate loss
            loss = criterion(output, target)
            
            # backward pass
            loss.backward()
            
            # optimization step
            optimizer.step()
            
            # update training loss
            train_loss += loss.item()*data.size(0)

            
            

            
        ### VALIDATION
        
        # set the model to evaluation mode
        model.eval()
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(valid_loader):
            # move to GPU
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
            
            # forward pass for prediction
            output = model(data)
            
            # loss calculation
            loss = criterion(output, target)
            
            

            ## TODO: update average validation loss 
            valid_loss += loss.item()*data.size(0)

        
        # for displaying epochs, get average losses
        train_loss = train_loss/len(train_loader.sampler)
        valid_loss = valid_loss/len(valid_loader.sampler)
            
            

        # print training/validation statistics 
        print(f'Epoch: {epoch} \tTraining Loss: {train_loss:.6f} \tValidation Loss: {valid_loss:.6f}')

        ## TODO: if the validation loss has decreased, save the model at the filepath stored in save_path
        if valid_loss <= valid_loss_min:
            print(f'Validation loss decreased ({valid_loss_min:.6f} --> {valid_loss:.6f}).  Saving model ...')
            
            torch.save(model.state_dict(), save_path)
            valid_loss_min = valid_loss        

        
        
    return model

from math import floor
import cv2
from PIL import Image

def process_image(image):

    # Manual processing of single fed image, to not to create a full dataloader structure
    # computationally more effective, images squared and center cropped along side lenghts
    # to adhere to Imagenet standard
    w, h = image.size
  
    size = 256, 256
    if w > h:
        ratio = float(w) / float(h)
        newh = ratio * size[0]
        image = image.resize((size[0], int(floor(newh))), Image.ANTIALIAS)
    else:
        ratio = float(h) / float(w)
        neww = ratio * size[0]
        image = image.resize((int(floor(neww)), size[0]), Image.ANTIALIAS)
    
    image = image.crop((
        size[0] //2 - (224/2),
        size[1] //2 - (224/2),
        size[0] //2 + (224/2),
        size[1] //2 + (224/2))
    )
    
    img_array = np.array(image)/255
    img_array[:,:,0] = (img_array[:,:,0] - 0.485)/(0.229)
    img_array[:,:,1] = (img_array[:,:,1] - 0.456)/(0.224)
    img_array[:,:,2] = (img_array[:,:,2] - 0.406)/(0.225)
    img_array = np.transpose(img_array, (2,0,1))
    
    return torch.FloatTensor([img_array])
In [28]:
import cv2
from PIL import Image
from torch.autograd import Variable
## the class names can be accessed at the `classes` attribute
## of your dataset object (e.g., `train_dataset.classes`)


def predict_landmarks(img_path, k):
    ## TODO: return the names of the top k landmarks predicted by the transfer learned CNN
    image = Image.open(img_path)
    image = process_image(image)
    image.to('cpu'), model_transfer.to('cpu')
    output = model_transfer(Variable(image))
    ps = torch.exp(output).data
    largest = ps.topk(k)
    prob = largest[0].numpy()[0]
    idx = largest[1].numpy()[0]
    classes = [train_set.classes[x] for x in idx]
    return prob, classes

# test on a sample image
predict_landmarks('images/test/09.Golden_Gate_Bridge/190f3bae17c32c37.jpg', 5)

def suggest_locations(img_path):
    # get landmark predictions
    prob, classes = predict_landmarks(img_path, 3)
    ## TODO: display image and display landmark predictions

    img = Image.open(img_path)
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,6), ncols=2, nrows=1)
    fig.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.5)
    landmark_label = img_path.split('/')[-2][3:].replace('_', " ")

    
    ax1.set_title(f'LABEL: {landmark_label}', fontsize=20, color="springgreen")
    ax1.imshow(img)
    ax1.axis('off')
    
    
    classes = [x[3:].replace("_", " ") for x in classes]
    
    y_pos = np.arange(len(prob))
    ax2.barh(y_pos, prob, align='edge', color="cyan", edgecolor="r")
    ax2.set_yticks(y_pos)
    ax2.set_yticklabels(classes, rotation=30)
    ax2.invert_yaxis()
    ax2.set_title('Most Probable Classes')
    
                
    print(f'"This location most likely is {classes[0]}, if not so, it may be {classes[1]}, or {classes[2]} "')
    
          
# test on a sample image
suggest_locations('images/test/16.Eiffel_Tower/3828627c8730f160.jpg')

"This location most likely is Eiffel Tower, if not so, it may be Sydney Harbour Bridge, or London Olympic Stadium "

(IMPLEMENTATION) Test Your Algorithm¶

Test your algorithm by running the suggest_locations function on at least four images on your computer. Feel free to use any images you like.

Question 4: Is the output better than you expected :) ? Or worse :( ? Provide at least three possible points of improvement for your algorithm.

Answer: (Three possible points for improvement) The outcome was better than expected given the small size of the dataset, also after having explored the images of selected classes manually, it was noticed that some of those images where relatively random and only general areas and in part random people where visible in those images, not even the landmark per se. It was expected for the CNN to achieve less accurate results than the transfer learning model, however for the limited time of experimenting with hyperparameters and the limited computing time invested in the model, the relative instant 44% accuracy showed that a production ready and useful model of 70-80% accuracy can very well be trained from scratch, in particular when implementing the following improvements to solve the problem:

  1. Enlargen the dataset in terms of more images per class and better selected images for those classes
  2. To make the model more useful for the general population more classes, respectively landmarks shall be added, the transfer learning approach should relatively easy compile to 1000 classes, since the original ImageNet dataset is comprised of 1000 classes.
  3. For the CNN I suspect to achieve higher accuracies with a higher number of epochs, and potentially use several workers for more data processing, further at a higher number of epochs the SGD optimizer is known to still improve the network, as such SGD should be used for those.
  4. Additional augmentation techniques should be applied, I suspect sharper and blurred augmentation techniques to make a differnce in day-night and limited visibility situations, those filter are amongst others GaussianBlur(), adn ColoJitter(), in this particular notebook this is not yet possible as those techniques are newly added to torchchvision and the docker container of the workspace has an older version of torchvision installed for compatibility reasons for projects created with prior torch versions.

Having that said, the overall outcome is impressive, the first chosen image was an attempt to trick the model with the Las Vegas rebuilt of the Eiffel Tower, and it was interesting that the shape was not weighed as high as color and environment what made sense when exploring the images of the Eiffel Tower class. The mountaineous panoramic areas chosen, both were not in the classes, but the prediction came close to the overall impression of those areas, which is good on one hand, but may also become problematic when adding more classes with mountaineous areas, the differentiation may suffer, as it did in the Central Park image from above which could not be differentiated from other urban areas. However, the model showed its strength with the Golden Gate Bridge and remarkable accuracy from both images from different perspectives, while also not incorrectly predicting the Bay Bridge above to be the Golden Gate Bridge.
